{"author":{"id":"cc8322a500b8739c77faac347808f6026d9ccb7880d0aaa7ad76754163cd7fdb"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782568927,"nonce":"O2pn0PJNWjQA0VEaxxJROQtMIJo=","kind":"plan","title":"kref Phase 2 (Tiers, Sync, lefthook) Implementation Plan"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782568927,"nonce":"6hQxhNE0Z6rECNVsGpopMv4IfO0=","body":"# kref Phase 2 (Tiers, Sync, lefthook) Implementation Plan\n\n\u003e **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: superpowers:subagent-driven-development. Steps use `- [ ]`. Tests: **Ginkgo v2 + Gomega only** (the `entry` package's specs are black-box `package entry_test`; others white-box). Run tests via `task test` (provisions gitleaks). Build to a temp path (`go build -o /tmp/kref-t ./cmd/kref`) â€” the in-container `./bin/kref` is a locked bind-mount artifact.\n\n**Goal:** Add the `kref-personal` tier, per-tier sync (`dag.Push`/`Pull`) routed to configured remotes with a hard `private`-never-leaves guard, a `kref sync`/`kref remote` CLI, and lefthook wiring that couples KB sync to git lifecycle events.\n\n**Architecture:** Tiers stay git ref namespaces (`kref-private|kref-personal|kref-shared`). Each tier maps to a git remote via local git config `kref.remote.\u003ctier\u003e` (private has none, ever). `dag.Push(def,repo,remote)` / `dag.Pull(def,wrap,repo,resolvers,remote,author)` move a whole namespace. lefthook runs `kref sync`/`kref ingest` on git hooks.\n\n**Verified API (v0.10.1):** `dag.Push(def, repo, remote) (string,error)`, `dag.Fetch(def, repo, remote) (string,error)`, `dag.Pull[E](def, wrap, repo, resolvers, remote, author) error`; `repo.AddRemote(name,url) error`, `repo.GetRemotes() (map[string]string,error)`; `repo.LocalConfig() repository.Config` with `ReadString(key)`, `StoreString(key,val)`, `ReadAll(prefix)`. `store` already has `repo`, `author`, `dir`, `resolvers`.\n\n**Out of scope (deferred):** distributed `purge --push` (force-deleting refs on remotes) â€” fragile break-glass; tracked as a follow-up after the sync core is solid.\n\n---\n\n### Task 1: Add the `kref-personal` tier + `--tier` flag\n\n**Files:** `internal/entry/entry.go`, `cmd/kref/commands.go`; tests `internal/store/store_test.go`, `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (test first):** store spec â€” add to a personal tier and read it back.\n```go\n// internal/store/store_test.go  (white-box package store)\nvar _ = Describe(\"Personal tier\", func() {\n\tIt(\"stores and reads an entry in the personal tier\", func() {\n\t\tdir := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\ts, err := Init(dir, \"T\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = s.Close() })\n\t\tid, err := s.Add(entry.TierPersonal, \"memory\", \"Mine\", \"x\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tgot, err := s.Get(id)\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(got.Tier).To(Equal(\"personal\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n- [ ] **Step 2:** run `go test ./internal/store/` â†’ FAIL (`entry.TierPersonal` undefined).\n- [ ] **Step 3:** in `internal/entry/entry.go` add the tier and include it in `AllTiers()`:\n```go\nconst (\n\tTierPrivate  Tier = \"private\"\n\tTierPersonal Tier = \"personal\"\n\tTierShared   Tier = \"shared\"\n)\n\n// AllTiers is the full set of tiers (order: private first so Get/List see it).\nfunc AllTiers() []Tier { return []Tier{TierPrivate, TierPersonal, TierShared} }\n```\n(`Definition`, clock loaders, `Get`/`List`/`Tombstone`/`Purge` all iterate `AllTiers()`, so they pick it up automatically.)\n- [ ] **Step 4:** Replace the `--private bool` flag on `add` and `ingest` with `--tier string` (default `shared`). Add a parser and use it; reject unknown values.\n```go\n// cmd/kref/commands.go\nfunc parseTier(s string) (entry.Tier, error) {\n\tswitch entry.Tier(s) {\n\tcase entry.TierPrivate, entry.TierPersonal, entry.TierShared:\n\t\treturn entry.Tier(s), nil\n\tdefault:\n\t\treturn \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"invalid --tier %q (want private|personal|shared)\", s)\n\t}\n}\n```\nIn `newAddCmd`/`newIngestCmd`: replace the `private` bool + `tierFrom` with a `var tier string` flag defaulting to `\"shared\"`, call `parseTier(tier)` at the top of RunE, and pass the result. Remove the now-unused `tierFrom`. Keep `bridge.Ingest`'s secretâ†’private quarantine (it overrides the chosen tier).\n- [ ] **Step 5:** CLI spec â€” `add --tier personal` then `show --json` shows `\"Tier\":\"personal\"`; `add --tier bogus` errors.\n- [ ] **Step 6:** `task test` green; `task lint`; commit `Add kref-personal tier and --tier flag`.\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Per-tier remote config + `store` sync (push/pull) with private guard\n\n**Files:** `internal/store/store.go` (+ new `internal/store/sync.go`); test `internal/store/sync_test.go` (+ suite already exists).\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (test first):** `internal/store/sync_test.go` â€” round-trip an entry between two stores over a file remote, and assert the private guard.\n```go\npackage store\n\nimport (\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/ginkgo/v2\"\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/gomega\"\n\n\t\"github.com/riotbox/kref/internal/entry\"\n)\n\nvar _ = Describe(\"Sync\", func() {\n\tIt(\"pushes a shared entry from one store and pulls it into another\", func() {\n\t\tdirA := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\tdirB := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\ta, err := Init(dirA, \"A\", \"a@e.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = a.Close() })\n\t\tb, err := Init(dirB, \"B\", \"b@e.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = b.Close() })\n\n\t\t// A and B point their \"shared\" tier at each other (file remotes).\n\t\tExpect(a.SetRemote(entry.TierShared, \"peer\", dirB)).To(Succeed())\n\t\tExpect(b.SetRemote(entry.TierShared, \"peer\", dirA)).To(Succeed())\n\n\t\tid, err := a.Add(entry.TierShared, \"spec\", \"Shared\", \"body\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(a.Push(entry.TierShared)).To(Succeed())\n\n\t\tExpect(b.Pull(entry.TierShared)).To(Succeed())\n\t\tgot, err := b.Get(id)\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(got.Title).To(Equal(\"Shared\"))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"refuses to push the private tier\", func() {\n\t\tdir := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\ts, err := Init(dir, \"A\", \"a@e.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = s.Close() })\n\t\tExpect(s.Push(entry.TierPrivate)).To(MatchError(ContainSubstring(\"private\")))\n\t})\n})\n```\n- [ ] **Step 2:** run â†’ FAIL (`SetRemote`, `Push`, `Pull` undefined).\n- [ ] **Step 3:** implement `internal/store/sync.go`:\n```go\npackage store\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\n\t\"github.com/git-bug/git-bug/entity/dag\"\n\n\t\"github.com/riotbox/kref/internal/entry\"\n)\n\nconst remoteConfigPrefix = \"kref.remote.\" // kref.remote.\u003ctier\u003e = \u003cremote name\u003e\n\n// SetRemote configures (and, if url != \"\", creates) the git remote for a tier.\n// The private tier may never have a remote.\nfunc (s *Store) SetRemote(t entry.Tier, name, url string) error {\n\tif t == entry.TierPrivate {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"the private tier cannot have a remote\")\n\t}\n\tif url != \"\" {\n\t\tif remotes, err := s.repo.GetRemotes(); err == nil {\n\t\t\tif _, exists := remotes[name]; !exists {\n\t\t\t\tif err := s.repo.AddRemote(name, url); err != nil {\n\t\t\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t} else {\n\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn s.repo.LocalConfig().StoreString(remoteConfigPrefix+string(t), name)\n}\n\n// RemoteFor returns the configured remote name for a tier, or \"\" if none.\nfunc (s *Store) RemoteFor(t entry.Tier) (string, error) {\n\tif t == entry.TierPrivate {\n\t\treturn \"\", nil\n\t}\n\tname, err := s.repo.LocalConfig().ReadString(remoteConfigPrefix + string(t))\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn \"\", nil // unset is not an error\n\t}\n\treturn name, nil\n}\n\n// Push sends a tier's entries to its configured remote. Private is always refused.\nfunc (s *Store) Push(t entry.Tier) error {\n\tif t == entry.TierPrivate {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"refusing to push the private tier\")\n\t}\n\tremote, err := s.RemoteFor(t)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn err\n\t}\n\tif remote == \"\" {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"no remote configured for tier %s (use `kref remote set %s \u003cname\u003e \u003curl\u003e`)\", t, t)\n\t}\n\t_, err = dag.Push(entry.Definition(t), s.repo, remote)\n\treturn err\n}\n\n// Pull fetches and merges a tier's entries from its configured remote.\nfunc (s *Store) Pull(t entry.Tier) error {\n\tif t == entry.TierPrivate {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"the private tier has no remote\")\n\t}\n\tremote, err := s.RemoteFor(t)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn err\n\t}\n\tif remote == \"\" {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"no remote configured for tier %s\", t)\n\t}\n\treturn dag.Pull(entry.Definition(t), entry.WrapForRead(), s.repo, resolvers(s.repo), remote, s.author)\n}\n\n// SyncableTiers are the non-private tiers that have a configured remote.\nfunc (s *Store) SyncableTiers() ([]entry.Tier, error) {\n\tvar out []entry.Tier\n\tfor _, t := range entry.AllTiers() {\n\t\tif t == entry.TierPrivate {\n\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t}\n\t\tr, err := s.RemoteFor(t)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\treturn nil, err\n\t\t}\n\t\tif r != \"\" {\n\t\t\tout = append(out, t)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn out, nil\n}\n```\n- [ ] **Step 4:** `task test` green (the sync round-trip and guard pass); `task lint`; commit `Add per-tier remote config and sync (push/pull) with private guard`.\n\nNOTE for the implementer: if `dag.Pull`/`Push` over a file-path remote errors, diagnose for real (e.g. confirm `AddRemote` stored the path; print the actual error) â€” do not weaken the assertions. The git-bug `entity/dag/example_test.go` does exactly this push/pull-over-local-path round-trip, so it is known to work.\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: `kref sync` + `kref remote` CLI\n\n**Files:** `cmd/kref/commands.go`, `cmd/kref/main.go`; test `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (test first):** CLI round-trip over a file remote, plus the private guard.\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"kref sync CLI\", func() {\n\tIt(\"pushes from A and pulls into B via configured remotes\", func() {\n\t\tdirA := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\tdirB := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dirA, \"init\", \"--name\", \"A\", \"--email\", \"a@e.com\")\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dirB, \"init\", \"--name\", \"B\", \"--email\", \"b@e.com\")\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dirA, \"remote\", \"set\", \"shared\", \"peer\", dirB)\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dirB, \"remote\", \"set\", \"shared\", \"peer\", dirA)\n\n\t\tout := run(\"--dir\", dirA, \"add\", \"--tier\", \"shared\", \"--title\", \"Hello\", \"--body\", \"x\")\n\t\tvar added struct{ ID string `json:\"id\"` }\n\t\tExpect(json.Unmarshal([]byte(out), \u0026added)).To(Succeed())\n\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dirA, \"sync\", \"push\", \"--tier\", \"shared\")\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dirB, \"sync\", \"pull\", \"--tier\", \"shared\")\n\t\tExpect(run(\"--dir\", dirB, \"list\", \"--json\")).To(ContainSubstring(\"Hello\"))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"errors when pushing the private tier\", func() {\n\t\tdir := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", \"--name\", \"A\", \"--email\", \"a@e.com\")\n\t\tvar out bytes.Buffer\n\t\tcmd := newRootCmd()\n\t\tcmd.SetOut(\u0026out)\n\t\tcmd.SetErr(\u0026out)\n\t\tcmd.SetArgs([]string{\"--dir\", dir, \"sync\", \"push\", \"--tier\", \"private\"})\n\t\tExpect(cmd.Execute()).To(HaveOccurred())\n\t})\n})\n```\n- [ ] **Step 2:** run â†’ FAIL (`remote`/`sync` commands undefined).\n- [ ] **Step 3:** implement `newRemoteCmd(dir)` with a `set \u003ctier\u003e \u003cname\u003e [url]` subcommand (calls `store.SetRemote`) and `newSyncCmd(dir)` with `push`/`pull` subcommands (default `--tier` empty = all syncable tiers, else the named tier). Register both in `main.go`'s `AddCommand`. `push`/`pull` with no `--tier` iterate `store.SyncableTiers()`; with `--tier private` they return the guard error. JSON output `{\"status\":\"pushed\"|\"pulled\",\"tier\":...}`.\n- [ ] **Step 4:** `task test` green; `task lint`; commit `Add kref sync and kref remote CLI`.\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: lefthook wiring (`kref hooks install`)\n\n**Files:** new `internal/hooks/hooks.go`; `cmd/kref/commands.go`, `cmd/kref/main.go`; tests `internal/hooks/hooks_suite_test.go`, `internal/hooks/hooks_test.go`, `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1 (test first):** `internal/hooks/hooks_test.go` â€” `Render()` produces a lefthook config containing the expected hookâ†’command wiring.\n```go\npackage hooks\n\nimport (\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/ginkgo/v2\"\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/gomega\"\n)\n\nvar _ = Describe(\"lefthook config\", func() {\n\tIt(\"wires sync pull/push and ingest to git lifecycle events\", func() {\n\t\tout := Render()\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"post-merge:\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"pre-push:\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"post-commit:\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref sync pull\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref sync push\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref ingest\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n(Plus a `hooks_suite_test.go` bootstrap: `RegisterFailHandler(Fail); RunSpecs(t, \"Hooks Suite\")`.)\n- [ ] **Step 2:** run â†’ FAIL (`Render` undefined).\n- [ ] **Step 3:** implement `internal/hooks/hooks.go` with a `Render() string` returning a lefthook YAML literal:\n```go\npackage hooks\n\n// Render returns a lefthook configuration wiring kref to git lifecycle events.\nfunc Render() string {\n\treturn `# Managed by ` + \"`kref hooks install`\" + `. lefthook (https://lefthook.dev) runs these.\npost-merge:\n  commands:\n    kref-sync-pull:\n      run: kref sync pull\npost-checkout:\n  commands:\n    kref-sync-pull:\n      run: kref sync pull\npre-push:\n  commands:\n    kref-sync-push:\n      run: kref sync push\npost-commit:\n  commands:\n    kref-ingest:\n      run: kref ingest\n`\n}\n\n// InstallPath is the conventional lefthook config filename.\nconst InstallPath = \"lefthook.yml\"\n```\n- [ ] **Step 4:** add `newHooksCmd(dir)` with an `install` subcommand: writes `Render()` to `\u003cdir\u003e/lefthook.yml` (error if it exists unless `--force`), and a `print` subcommand that writes `Render()` to stdout. Register in `main.go`. CLI spec: `hooks print` output contains `pre-push:`; `hooks install` then the file exists with the content.\n- [ ] **Step 5:** `task test` green; `task lint`; commit `Add kref hooks install (lefthook wiring)`.\n\n---\n\n## Self-Review\n- **Spec coverage (Â§9 Phase 2):** `kref-personal` (Task 1) âś…; per-tier sync routing + tier-guard (Tasks 2â€“3) âś…; lefthook wiring (Task 4) âś…. Distributed `purge --push` is explicitly deferred (noted above) â€” update Â§8/Â§9 if it lands later.\n- **Type consistency:** `entry.TierPersonal`, `store.SetRemote/RemoteFor/Push/Pull/SyncableTiers`, `parseTier`, `hooks.Render`/`InstallPath` â€” used identically across tasks.\n- **Tests at every step:** each task is redâ†’green with a real assertion (sync uses a genuine two-repo file-remote round-trip, not a stub)."}]}